basidiospores with cross striae on the ridges and spirally encrusted hyphae in the marginal appendiculae and stipe trama. Macrocharacters-pileus 33-74 mm wide, convex to planoconvex, with appressed to recurved squamules, red-brown (10B7-10D7) to red-tan (7D5-8D4-8E5) to pink (9A4-10B4) to pink-grey (10C4), vestiture concentrated and more squarrose on disk, extending out of cream (1A2-3A2-3A3-4A3) to light orange-pink (7A3) to light pink-red (9A6) floccose ground; margin entire and clasping stipe when young, at maturity separating into triangular appendiculae, these 6-12 x 3-10 mm, buff white (5A3-5B4), occasionally faint pink; moist; trama 2-3 mm thick at margin, 7-10 mm over tubes, 11-18 mm centrally, buff white to light yellow (3A3), rapidly bluing (23C7) upon exposure, solid; tubes 1-5 mm long at margin, 10-20 mm centrally, 4-6 mm at stipe, broadly and deeply depressed around stipe, of irregular lengths, bright yellow (3A8) to olive yellow (2B7-3B7-3C7) to mustard yellow (4A8-4B8), rapidly bluing (23C7) upon exposure; pores concolorous with tubes, rapidly blue-green (23C8) with pressure, 0.5-1.5 per mm, angular; stipe 53-115 x 6-14 mm broad, subequal, gradually enlarging toward base to 10-19 mm, apical portion cream (3A4) to pink (9A4), middle portion finely longitudinally striate, striations darkening with handling, red-1avender (11A6-11B4-11B7-11B8) to brownred (9E8-10E8), lighter with age, immediately above basal tomentum cream (3A2-3A4) with few striations; basal tomentum of white strigose hairs over lower 6-50 mm, occasionally subtended by ectomycorrhizal rootlets; trama white to buff-tan (5B4) to light yellow (3A4), slightly bluing with exposure; solid; odor non-descript; taste mild. Microcharacters-basidiospores olivaceous-brown (4D7-4E7-5E6-5F6) in medium to heavy deposit, 17.5-22.2 x 6.4-8 µm

basidiospores from A. areolatum and A. chailletii showed a distinct différence in size. The spores of A. areolatum were within the range 3,6-5,6 x 2-3,2 µm,

basidiospores of A. areolatum are noticably smaller that those of A. chailletii, and the différence can be recognized by visual observation of spore prints without measuring. Storing the basidiospore prints caused the spores to shrink slightly. The length of the basidiospores in fresh prints did not approach the lower limits of the range seen in stored prints. Thus fresh basidiospores were never less than 4 µm

basidiospores and always for the average basidiospore size. In stored sporeprints, many spores of A. areolatum conformed to the ratio associated with A. chailletii, i.e. spore length twice the width or longer. However, in average the length was less than two times the width in all cases except one (Table 2). In stored sporeprints of A. chailletii the average basidiospore length was generally twice the width, but some notable exceptions occured (Table 2) which is reflected in the length/width ratio for stored spores (Table 1).  Table 1 Summary of basidiospore sizes (fresh and preserved prints) for A. areolatum and A. chailletii measured in lactophenol. A. areolatum A. chailletii Average, fresh 4,6 x 2,6 µm,

basidiospores were consistently smaller than A. chailletii-spores. A. chailletii spores were more variable in size, although their average length did not vary much. The average spore width of A. chailletii was much more variable than the average spore length . Single basidiospores of A. chailletii might approach the smaller size of A. areolatum spores, but in average (of 25 spores) they were always longer and wider . As a rule, Amylostereum chailletii spores are nearly always 5 µm,

basidiospores are slightly thick-walled, as in other species of Crustoderma. Crustoderma sabinicum is very similar to C. dryinum (Berk. et Curtis) Parm. but can be distinguished by three critical characters. First, the basidiocarps of the former species are lighter in color (Pale Ochraceous Buff with white margins) than in the latter. Second, although the basidiospore size overlaps, they are slightly wider in C. sabinicum (7-9 x (3.5-)4-4.5 µm)

basidiospores clearly distinguishes the species. The hyphal system is dimitic with long, undextrinoid, primarily arboriform skeletal hyphae in the context and in the trama of the tubes, although the branching is more difficult to interpret in the latter. This branching pattern corresponds to the description given by Corner (1989) for his own collections identified as P. clelandii, with an ill-defined arboriform branching pattern, and occasionally tortuous, geniculated, profusely branched narrow vegetative hyphae. The hyphal system, hyphal make-up and basidiospore morphology support the inclusion in Perenniporia, according to the current definition of the genus (Corner 1989; Decock and Ryvarden 1999a; 1999b; Gilbertson and Ryvarden 1987; Ryvarden and Johansen 1980; Ryvarden and Gilbertson 1994).  Cunningham reported 5-6 pores /mm with a pore diameter of 80-112 µm,

Basidiospores and hyphal system are identical to those found in the type specimen of P. clelandii. It might represent a different form or variety but, for the time being, and notwithstanding the differences noted, we include the specimen in P. clelandii, pending availability of more material.  The taxon is poorly known and we have found few reports of it in literature. Three specimens named F. clelandii are available in the Lloyd Mycological Collections (BPI) but only the type specimen is fertile. Furthermore, the specimen cat. no. 37945 is of doubtful identity, as already noted by Cunningham (1965) who identified it as T. scutellata (Schw.) G. Cunn. basidiospores are musiform to subfusiform and appear to be nonseptate when shed. In germinated spores, one to three septa are present , as in some species of Exobasidium, and small ellipsoid conidia are produced at the ends of the basidiospore. The conidiogenous peg elongates, with sympodial production of successive conidia, and develops into an irregular tubular structure. The basidiospores are 10-12 x 3-4.5 µm;

basidiospores of Ryv. 9877 resemble those of B. donkii, but accurate identification of these African collections needs further study and the distribution of B. lacticolor in Africa remains questionable. Hjortstam (1987) considered B. donkii to be a synonym of B. lacticolor, but as mentioned above the former has larger basidiospores. Hjortstam and Larsson (1994) identified a specimen from India (deposited in K) as B. lacticolor. This specimen was originally named by Dr. Rattan as Gloeocystidiellum odontioides, but this name has not been formally published. We also found a New Zealand specimen (PDD 13783) with characters similar to B. lacticolor including spores 4-5 x 3.5-4.5 µm,

basidiospores are slightly thick-walled, as in other species of Crustoderma. Crustoderma sabinicum is very similar to C. dryinum (Berk. et Curtis) Parm. but can be distinguished by three critical characters. First, the basidiocarps of the former species are lighter in color (Pale Ochraceous Buff with white margins) than in the latter. Second, although the basidiospore size overlaps, they are slightly wider in C. sabinicum (7-9 x (3.5-)4-4.5 µm)

basidiospores of Ryv. 9877 resemble those of B. donkii, but accurate identification of these African collections needs further study and the distribution of B. lacticolor in Africa remains questionable. Hjortstam (1987) considered B. donkii to be a synonym of B. lacticolor, but as mentioned above the former has larger basidiospores. Hjortstam and Larsson (1994) identified a specimen from India (deposited in K) as B. lacticolor. This specimen was originally named by Dr. Rattan as Gloeocystidiellum odontioides, but this name has not been formally published. We also found a New Zealand specimen (PDD 13783) with characters similar to B. lacticolor including spores 4-5 x 3.5-4.5 µm,

Pilear cover (Fig. 10b) a cortex formed by hyphae slightly inclined to the context hyphae, predominantly composed of skeletal, subhyaline to yellowish, thick-walled, intermingled with generative, clamped, thinwalled, usually collapsed hyphae. basidiospores together distinguish Hyphodontia ochroflava from other species of Hyphodontia. An unusual feature of H. ochroflava is the development of lagenocystidia on vegetative hyphae at the base of the spines. These lagenocystidia are produced laterally, at right angles on supporting hyphae and often lack the characteristic flask shape. Another important feature is the somewhat thick-to thick-walled tramal hyphae of the central spine that superficially resemble skeletal hyphae. Hyphodontia ochroflava is closely related to H. arguta (Fr.) John Erikss. that possesses significantly broader basidiospores (4.5-6 x 3.5-4 µm).

basidiospores clearly distinguishes the species. The hyphal system is dimitic with long, undextrinoid, primarily arboriform skeletal hyphae in the context and in the trama of the tubes, although the branching is more difficult to interpret in the latter. This branching pattern corresponds to the description given by Corner (1989) for his own collections identified as P. clelandii, with an ill-defined arboriform branching pattern, and occasionally tortuous, geniculated, profusely branched narrow vegetative hyphae. The hyphal system, hyphal make-up and basidiospore morphology support the inclusion in Perenniporia, according to the current definition of the genus (Corner 1989; Decock and Ryvarden 1999a; 1999b; Gilbertson and Ryvarden 1987; Ryvarden and Johansen 1980; Ryvarden and Gilbertson 1994).  Cunningham reported 5-6 pores /mm with a pore diameter of 80-112 µm,

Basidiospores and hyphal system are identical to those found in the type specimen of P. clelandii. It might represent a different form or variety but, for the time being, and notwithstanding the differences noted, we include the specimen in P. clelandii, pending availability of more material.  The taxon is poorly known and we have found few reports of it in literature. Three specimens named F. clelandii are available in the Lloyd Mycological Collections (BPI) but only the type specimen is fertile. Furthermore, the specimen cat. no. 37945 is of doubtful identity, as already noted by Cunningham (1965) who identified it as T. scutellata (Schw.) G. Cunn. basidiospores with cross striae on the ridges and spirally encrusted hyphae in the marginal appendiculae and stipe trama. Macrocharacters-pileus 33-74 mm wide, convex to planoconvex, with appressed to recurved squamules, red-brown (10B7-10D7) to red-tan (7D5-8D4-8E5) to pink (9A4-10B4) to pink-grey (10C4), vestiture concentrated and more squarrose on disk, extending out of cream (1A2-3A2-3A3-4A3) to light orange-pink (7A3) to light pink-red (9A6) floccose ground; margin entire and clasping stipe when young, at maturity separating into triangular appendiculae, these 6-12 x 3-10 mm, buff white (5A3-5B4), occasionally faint pink; moist; trama 2-3 mm thick at margin, 7-10 mm over tubes, 11-18 mm centrally, buff white to light yellow (3A3), rapidly bluing (23C7) upon exposure, solid; tubes 1-5 mm long at margin, 10-20 mm centrally, 4-6 mm at stipe, broadly and deeply depressed around stipe, of irregular lengths, bright yellow (3A8) to olive yellow (2B7-3B7-3C7) to mustard yellow (4A8-4B8), rapidly bluing (23C7) upon exposure; pores concolorous with tubes, rapidly blue-green (23C8) with pressure, 0.5-1.5 per mm, angular; stipe 53-115 x 6-14 mm broad, subequal, gradually enlarging toward base to 10-19 mm, apical portion cream (3A4) to pink (9A4), middle portion finely longitudinally striate, striations darkening with handling, red-1avender (11A6-11B4-11B7-11B8) to brownred (9E8-10E8), lighter with age, immediately above basal tomentum cream (3A2-3A4) with few striations; basal tomentum of white strigose hairs over lower 6-50 mm, occasionally subtended by ectomycorrhizal rootlets; trama white to buff-tan (5B4) to light yellow (3A4), slightly bluing with exposure; solid; odor non-descript; taste mild. Microcharacters-basidiospores olivaceous-brown (4D7-4E7-5E6-5F6) in medium to heavy deposit, 17.5-22.2 x 6.4-8 µm

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). Basidiospores in A. mirabilis are larger, ovoidellipsoid to ellipsoid, semilunate, biapiculate, and appear decidedly asperate in Melzer's. Spores in A. croceus are subgloboid to ovoid, and appear minutely verrucose-echinulate in Melzer's. Acanthophyses in A. croceus lack the acicular-curved prongs frequently found in specimens of A. mirabilis. The two species are further distinguished on texture and basidiole size. A. ochraceo-flavus Lloyd from New Zealand is similar to A. croceus, but differs in possessing smaller basidioles, 80-100 x 16-20 µm

basidiospores of Ryv. 9877 resemble those of B. donkii, but accurate identification of these African collections needs further study and the distribution of B. lacticolor in Africa remains questionable. Hjortstam (1987) considered B. donkii to be a synonym of B. lacticolor, but as mentioned above the former has larger basidiospores. Hjortstam and Larsson (1994) identified a specimen from India (deposited in K) as B. lacticolor. This specimen was originally named by Dr. Rattan as Gloeocystidiellum odontioides, but this name has not been formally published. We also found a New Zealand specimen (PDD 13783) with characters similar to B. lacticolor including spores 4-5 x 3.5-4.5 µm,

Temburong District, Belalong Field Centre, by river on rotten decorticated log, 17 March 1992, Spooner B440, K(M) 43726 (holotype of Scopulodontia loricata: K); Sungai Belalong, riverside track near Field Centre, on rotten log, 21 March 192, Spooner B587, K(M) 28122 (paratype of S. loricata, K). NEW ZEALAND. Otago, Ulva, Stewart Island, on bark of Weinmannia racemosa Linn.f., 18 Feb. 1954, J.M. Dingley, PDD 18041 (holotype of Odontia tessellata: PDD). This striking species is immediately identifiable because of the stratified, rimose, dense basidiomes with rounded tubercules, encrusted, thick-walled cystidia, and small, ellipsoid basidiospores. Although the holotype specimen of O. latemarginata lacks basidia, it is otherwise morphologically similar to S. loricata and O. tessellata. The holotype specimen of Odontia tessellata is a particularly fine, extensively rimose, and well-developed specimen with the largest piece measuring 15 x 7 cm. The paratype specimen of S. loricata from Ecuador (on wood, T. Laessoe TL-155, K(M) 55757 (K)) differs from the holotype specimen of S. loricata by its longer (up to 2 mm), brittle, smooth, cylindrical spines, slightly shorter and narrower cystidia (25-50 x 5-6.5 µm),

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). Patouillard & Gaillard (1888: 27) reported the species in Venezuela and indicated the basidiospores as hyaline and 6-7 µm

Basidiospores in A. mirabilis are larger, ovoidellipsoid to ellipsoid, semilunate, biapiculate, and appear decidedly asperate in Melzer's. Spores in A. croceus are subgloboid to ovoid, and appear minutely verrucose-echinulate in Melzer's. Acanthophyses in A. croceus lack the acicular-curved prongs frequently found in specimens of A. mirabilis. The two species are further distinguished on texture and basidiole size. A. ochraceo-flavus Lloyd from New Zealand is similar to A. croceus, but differs in possessing smaller basidioles, 80-100 x 16-20 µm

In stored sporeprints, many spores of A. areolatum conformed to the ratio associated with A. chailletii, i.e. spore length twice the width or longer. However, in average the length was less than two times the width in all cases except one (Table 2). In stored sporeprints of A. chailletii the average basidiospore length was generally twice the width, but some notable exceptions occured (Table 2) which is reflected in the length/width ratio for stored spores (Table 1).  Table 1 Summary of basidiospore sizes (fresh and preserved prints) for A. areolatum and A. chailletii measured in lactophenol. A. areolatum A. chailletii Average, fresh 4,6 x 2,6 µm,

basidiospores were consistently smaller than A. chailletii-spores. A. chailletii spores were more variable in size, although their average length did not vary much. The average spore width of A. chailletii was much more variable than the average spore length . Single basidiospores of A. chailletii might approach the smaller size of A. areolatum spores, but in average (of 25 spores) they were always longer and wider . basidiospores of A. canadensis are ellipsoid and rounded at both ends, whereas spores in A. fennicus are distinctly flattened adaxially and taper toward the apiculus. The macrocystidia of A. fennicus are generally flexuous-cylindric to subclavate, whereas the macrocystidia found in A. canadensis are regularly one to several moniliform toward the apex. Spore dimensions cited for European material of this species are rather small for the North American material (fide Laurila, 10-14 x 7-9 µm).

basidiospores together distinguish Hyphodontia ochroflava from other species of Hyphodontia. An unusual feature of H. ochroflava is the development of lagenocystidia on vegetative hyphae at the base of the spines. These lagenocystidia are produced laterally, at right angles on supporting hyphae and often lack the characteristic flask shape. Another important feature is the somewhat thick-to thick-walled tramal hyphae of the central spine that superficially resemble skeletal hyphae. Hyphodontia ochroflava is closely related to H. arguta (Fr.) John Erikss. that possesses significantly broader basidiospores (4.5-6 x 3.5-4 µm).

basidiospores (a) Potato isolate (i) On host: Hymenial development on the fungus growth around the dead host tissue lying on the surface of the wet soil was not conspicuously marked out. However, on critical and daily observations it can be seen by a trained eye. A typical aerial, slightly powdery, velvety, whitish growth started appearing after 39 to 40 days. The creeping mycelium gave out such growth, which was scarcely formed near the edges of the spot or even in the centre. When this growth was carefully picked up and mounted in Amann's lactophenol with little cotton blue, it consisted of a circular cushion like hymenial development bearing basidia on the outer side of the hymenial layer. Basidium was comparatively short, stout, slightly thin with a septum at the base delimiting it from the hymenium, and measured 10-20 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth, obclavate and measured 2.5-7 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth obclavate and measured 4.2-9.6  µm

basidiospores on the uric acid were more or less of the same type. (b) Colocasia isolate: On modified Lewis's medium containing vitamine E, uric acid medium with reduced carbon source, onion proteose peptone and on calcium carbonate medium, hymenial production consisted of aerial, button like, loosely formed white growth. On uric acid, however, this growth consisting of a chain of hymenia, started developing on the surface or on the sides of the petri dish in 50 to 60 days. This growth measured 0.20 to 0.75 mm on other media but on uric acid it measured 1 cm x 3 cm. It could be differentiated from the young sclerotium by its loose, velvety and white appearance which was maintained throughout. On microscopic examinations the growth on vitamine E consisted of numerous hymenia with many abortive basidia and a few well developed basidia having 1 to 4 sterigmata. Basidia, however, in this case, appeared club shaped, slender but not stout and measured 20-30 µm

The shape and manner of developing the hymenia were more or less similar to those noticed in Colocasia isolate. Hymenial structures measured 0.10 to 0.75 mm. Basidia were club shaped and slender as those of Colocasia isolate and were scarcely formed. They measured 20-25 µm

basidiospores most frequent in a zone between the margin and the chlamysdospore-producing, farinaceous part. Colony radius 20 mm after 6 weeks. The cultural characters of X. tulasnelloidea were also studied by Boidin (1958), with similar results. Code: 2a. 3c. 11. 34. 36. 38. 47. 48. 54. 58. 61. Oxidase reactions: Syringaldazine, 1-Naphtol, Gum Guaiac, Guaiacol positive. p-Cresol and L-Tyrosin negative. Cytology: SS-mycelia with uninucleate cells, PS-mycelium dicaryotic, conidia binucleate. Nuclear behaviour: Normal. Culture characters (GB 1532 = "Central European type"): The only differences between this culture and those representing the "Nordic type" seem to be bigger chlamydospores (7.5-12 x 4-4.5 um versus 4.5-6 x 3.5-4.3 µm)

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). Patouillard & Gaillard (1888: 27) reported the species in Venezuela and indicated the basidiospores as hyaline and 6-7 µm

basidiospores of A. areolatum are noticably smaller that those of A. chailletii, and the différence can be recognized by visual observation of spore prints without measuring. Storing the basidiospore prints caused the spores to shrink slightly. In stored sporeprints, many spores of A. areolatum conformed to the ratio associated with A. chailletii, i.e. spore length twice the width or longer. However, in average the length was less than two times the width in all cases except one (Table 2). In stored sporeprints of A. chailletii the average basidiospore length was generally twice the width, but some notable exceptions occured (Table 2) which is reflected in the length/width ratio for stored spores (Table 1).  Table 1 Summary of basidiospore sizes (fresh and preserved prints) for A. areolatum and A. chailletii measured in lactophenol. A. areolatum A. chailletii Average, fresh 4,6 x 2,6 µm,

basidiospores (a) Potato isolate (i) On host: Hymenial development on the fungus growth around the dead host tissue lying on the surface of the wet soil was not conspicuously marked out. However, on critical and daily observations it can be seen by a trained eye. A typical aerial, slightly powdery, velvety, whitish growth started appearing after 39 to 40 days. The creeping mycelium gave out such growth, which was scarcely formed near the edges of the spot or even in the centre. When this growth was carefully picked up and mounted in Amann's lactophenol with little cotton blue, it consisted of a circular cushion like hymenial development bearing basidia on the outer side of the hymenial layer. Basidium was comparatively short, stout, slightly thin with a septum at the base delimiting it from the hymenium, and measured 10-20 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth, obclavate and measured 2.5-7 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth obclavate and measured 4.2-9.6  µm

basidiospores on the uric acid were more or less of the same type. (b) Colocasia isolate: On modified Lewis's medium containing vitamine E, uric acid medium with reduced carbon source, onion proteose peptone and on calcium carbonate medium, hymenial production consisted of aerial, button like, loosely formed white growth. On uric acid, however, this growth consisting of a chain of hymenia, started developing on the surface or on the sides of the petri dish in 50 to 60 days. This growth measured 0.20 to 0.75 mm on other media but on uric acid it measured 1 cm x 3 cm. It could be differentiated from the young sclerotium by its loose, velvety and white appearance which was maintained throughout. On microscopic examinations the growth on vitamine E consisted of numerous hymenia with many abortive basidia and a few well developed basidia having 1 to 4 sterigmata. Basidia, however, in this case, appeared club shaped, slender but not stout and measured 20-30 µm

The shape and manner of developing the hymenia were more or less similar to those noticed in Colocasia isolate. Hymenial structures measured 0.10 to 0.75 mm. basidiospores were observed. On the original material at L, of which I had no knowledge in-1967, I can find no clamps on hyphae or basidia. The hymenium will not support observation, for the basidia are so gelatinized as to be shapeless, except for a rare apex protruding from the hymenial surface. basidiospores of A. areolatum are noticably smaller that those of A. chailletii, and the différence can be recognized by visual observation of spore prints without measuring. Storing the basidiospore prints caused the spores to shrink slightly. The length of the basidiospores in fresh prints did not approach the lower limits of the range seen in stored prints. Thus fresh basidiospores were never less than 4 µm

basidiospores and always for the average basidiospore size. In stored sporeprints, many spores of A. areolatum conformed to the ratio associated with A. chailletii, i.e. spore length twice the width or longer. However, in average the length was less than two times the width in all cases except one (Table 2). In stored sporeprints of A. chailletii the average basidiospore length was generally twice the width, but some notable exceptions occured (Table 2) which is reflected in the length/width ratio for stored spores (Table 1).  Table 1 Summary of basidiospore sizes (fresh and preserved prints) for A. areolatum and A. chailletii measured in lactophenol. A. areolatum A. chailletii Average, fresh 4,6 x 2,6 µm,

basidiospores were consistently smaller than A. chailletii-spores. A. chailletii spores were more variable in size, although their average length did not vary much. The average spore width of A. chailletii was much more variable than the average spore length . Single basidiospores of A. chailletii might approach the smaller size of A. areolatum spores, but in average (of 25 spores) they were always longer and wider . As a rule, Amylostereum chailletii spores are nearly always 5 µm,

basidiospores (a) Potato isolate (i) On host: Hymenial development on the fungus growth around the dead host tissue lying on the surface of the wet soil was not conspicuously marked out. However, on critical and daily observations it can be seen by a trained eye. A typical aerial, slightly powdery, velvety, whitish growth started appearing after 39 to 40 days. The creeping mycelium gave out such growth, which was scarcely formed near the edges of the spot or even in the centre. When this growth was carefully picked up and mounted in Amann's lactophenol with little cotton blue, it consisted of a circular cushion like hymenial development bearing basidia on the outer side of the hymenial layer. Basidium was comparatively short, stout, slightly thin with a septum at the base delimiting it from the hymenium, and measured 10-20 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth, obclavate and measured 2.5-7 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth obclavate and measured 4.2-9.6  µm

basidiospores on the uric acid were more or less of the same type. (b) Colocasia isolate: On modified Lewis's medium containing vitamine E, uric acid medium with reduced carbon source, onion proteose peptone and on calcium carbonate medium, hymenial production consisted of aerial, button like, loosely formed white growth. On uric acid, however, this growth consisting of a chain of hymenia, started developing on the surface or on the sides of the petri dish in 50 to 60 days. This growth measured 0.20 to 0.75 mm on other media but on uric acid it measured 1 cm x 3 cm. It could be differentiated from the young sclerotium by its loose, velvety and white appearance which was maintained throughout. On microscopic examinations the growth on vitamine E consisted of numerous hymenia with many abortive basidia and a few well developed basidia having 1 to 4 sterigmata. Basidia, however, in this case, appeared club shaped, slender but not stout and measured 20-30 µm

basidiospores were of smaller size on uric acid. (c) Groundnut isolate: In this isolate, hymenial formation was seen only on the sides of the petri dish poured with modified Lewis's medium containing vitamin E, but was spread in the sub-centre on uric acid medium with less carbon source. The shape and manner of developing the hymenia were more or less similar to those noticed in Colocasia isolate. Hymenial structures measured 0.10 to 0.75 mm. Basidiospores were of the same shape as in the other isolates, but they were slightly smaller in size, measuring 5 to 6 µm

basidiospores in the lumina. Pores 1-3 mm diam, angular, with edges being entire or lacerate, thin; poroid surface concolorous with that formed by the tubular profiles. Stipe solid or tubular, sometimes branched, giving origin to separate pilei or forming a single pileus on top. Microscopic characteristics. Pilear cover (Fig. 10b) a cortex formed by hyphae slightly inclined to the context hyphae, predominantly composed of skeletal, subhyaline to yellowish, thick-walled, intermingled with generative, clamped, thinwalled, usually collapsed hyphae. Peripherally the hyphae agglutinated by an exudate making them darker, but exudate not oozing onto the surface. Cortex slightly incrusted peripherally in old basidiocarps. Context composed mainly of hyaline, subhyaline to yellowish, hyphae; generative hyphae clamped, hyaline, thin-walled, 2-4(-5) µm

basidiospores (a) Potato isolate (i) On host: Hymenial development on the fungus growth around the dead host tissue lying on the surface of the wet soil was not conspicuously marked out. However, on critical and daily observations it can be seen by a trained eye. A typical aerial, slightly powdery, velvety, whitish growth started appearing after 39 to 40 days. The creeping mycelium gave out such growth, which was scarcely formed near the edges of the spot or even in the centre. When this growth was carefully picked up and mounted in Amann's lactophenol with little cotton blue, it consisted of a circular cushion like hymenial development bearing basidia on the outer side of the hymenial layer. Basidium was comparatively short, stout, slightly thin with a septum at the base delimiting it from the hymenium, and measured 10-20 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth, obclavate and measured 2.5-7 µm
Basidiospores were hyaline, smooth obclavate and measured 4.2-9.6  µm

basidiospores on the uric acid were more or less of the same type. (b) Colocasia isolate: On modified Lewis's medium containing vitamine E, uric acid medium with reduced carbon source, onion proteose peptone and on calcium carbonate medium, hymenial production consisted of aerial, button like, loosely formed white growth. On uric acid, however, this growth consisting of a chain of hymenia, started developing on the surface or on the sides of the petri dish in 50 to 60 days. This growth measured 0.20 to 0.75 mm on other media but on uric acid it measured 1 cm x 3 cm. It could be differentiated from the young sclerotium by its loose, velvety and white appearance which was maintained throughout. On microscopic examinations the growth on vitamine E consisted of numerous hymenia with many abortive basidia and a few well developed basidia having 1 to 4 sterigmata. Basidia, however, in this case, appeared club shaped, slender but not stout and measured 20-30 µm

basidiospores clearly distinguishes the species. The hyphal system is dimitic with long, undextrinoid, primarily arboriform skeletal hyphae in the context and in the trama of the tubes, although the branching is more difficult to interpret in the latter. This branching pattern corresponds to the description given by Corner (1989) for his own collections identified as P. clelandii, with an ill-defined arboriform branching pattern, and occasionally tortuous, geniculated, profusely branched narrow vegetative hyphae. The hyphal system, hyphal make-up and basidiospore morphology support the inclusion in Perenniporia, according to the current definition of the genus (Corner 1989; Decock and Ryvarden 1999a; 1999b; Gilbertson and Ryvarden 1987; Ryvarden and Johansen 1980; Ryvarden and Gilbertson 1994).  Cunningham reported 5-6 pores /mm with a pore diameter of 80-112 µm,

Basidiospores and hyphal system are identical to those found in the type specimen of P. clelandii. It might represent a different form or variety but, for the time being, and notwithstanding the differences noted, we include the specimen in P. clelandii, pending availability of more material.  The taxon is poorly known and we have found few reports of it in literature. Three specimens named F. clelandii are available in the Lloyd Mycological Collections (BPI) but only the type specimen is fertile. Furthermore, the specimen cat. no. 37945 is of doubtful identity, as already noted by Cunningham (1965) who identified it as T. scutellata (Schw.) G. Cunn. Corner (1989) reported several collections from Malaysia, for which he described basidiospores as 4.0-5.0 x 3.5-4.0 µm,

basidiospores 5.7-6.0 mm long in the specimen 1153, which is below the range reported here for the species, and 8.0-9.5 mm for specimen 1154, which fits within our observations. These two STE specimens were not available for comparison and their identity remain uncertain.  P. vicina is characterized by a pileate basidiocarp, a dimitic hyphal system with arboriform skeletal hyphae in the tubes trama, subglobose to obovoid, dextrinoid basidiospores with a small "germ pore" opposite the apiculus and dextrinoid chlamydospores.  The two South African specimens examined are very similar, while the Zimbabwean specimen slightly differs. The latter has a more blackish crust developing from the base, and microscopically, has arboriform skeletal hyphae with a longer stalk (up to 450 mm, average 309 mm) (Table I). A black crust was described in Polyporus nigro-applanatus van der Byl (1924) but the type of the latter was not available for comparison, and we are not confident of its status. We therefore consider it as synonym of P. vicina, following Reid (1973; 1975) and Ryvarden and Johansen (1980).  Within the known range of occurrence (South and East Africa), P. vicina can be compared to Vanderbylia ungulata Reid (1973), a taxon usually known under Perenniporia mundula (Wakef.) Ryvarden (Ryvarden and Johansen, 1980). V. ungulata is characterized by large, perennial basidiocarp, with stratified pore layers and a thick black crust often becoming rimose with age, smaller basidiospores (5.5-6.8 x 5.2-6.2 µm

basidiospores of A. canadensis are ellipsoid and rounded at both ends, whereas spores in A. fennicus are distinctly flattened adaxially and taper toward the apiculus. The macrocystidia of A. fennicus are generally flexuous-cylindric to subclavate, whereas the macrocystidia found in A. canadensis are regularly one to several moniliform toward the apex. Spore dimensions cited for European material of this species are rather small for the North American material (fide Laurila, 10-14 x 7-9 µm).

basidiospores are musiform to subfusiform and appear to be nonseptate when shed. In germinated spores, one to three septa are present , as in some species of Exobasidium, and small ellipsoid conidia are produced at the ends of the basidiospore. The conidiogenous peg elongates, with sympodial production of successive conidia, and develops into an irregular tubular structure. The basidiospores are 10-12 x 3-4.5 µm;

basidiospores clearly distinguishes the species. The hyphal system is dimitic with long, undextrinoid, primarily arboriform skeletal hyphae in the context and in the trama of the tubes, although the branching is more difficult to interpret in the latter. This branching pattern corresponds to the description given by Corner (1989) for his own collections identified as P. clelandii, with an ill-defined arboriform branching pattern, and occasionally tortuous, geniculated, profusely branched narrow vegetative hyphae. The hyphal system, hyphal make-up and basidiospore morphology support the inclusion in Perenniporia, according to the current definition of the genus (Corner 1989; Decock and Ryvarden 1999a; 1999b; Gilbertson and Ryvarden 1987; Ryvarden and Johansen 1980; Ryvarden and Gilbertson 1994).  Cunningham reported 5-6 pores /mm with a pore diameter of 80-112 µm,

Basidiospores and hyphal system are identical to those found in the type specimen of P. clelandii. It might represent a different form or variety but, for the time being, and notwithstanding the differences noted, we include the specimen in P. clelandii, pending availability of more material.  The taxon is poorly known and we have found few reports of it in literature. Three specimens named F. clelandii are available in the Lloyd Mycological Collections (BPI) but only the type specimen is fertile. Furthermore, the specimen cat. no. 37945 is of doubtful identity, as already noted by Cunningham (1965) who identified it as T. scutellata (Schw.) G. Cunn. Corner (1989) reported several collections from Malaysia, for which he described basidiospores as 4.0-5.0 x 3.5-4.0 µm,

basidiospores 5.7-6.0 mm long in the specimen 1153, which is below the range reported here for the species, and 8.0-9.5 mm for specimen 1154, which fits within our observations. These two STE specimens were not available for comparison and their identity remain uncertain.  P. vicina is characterized by a pileate basidiocarp, a dimitic hyphal system with arboriform skeletal hyphae in the tubes trama, subglobose to obovoid, dextrinoid basidiospores with a small "germ pore" opposite the apiculus and dextrinoid chlamydospores.  The two South African specimens examined are very similar, while the Zimbabwean specimen slightly differs. The latter has a more blackish crust developing from the base, and microscopically, has arboriform skeletal hyphae with a longer stalk (up to 450 mm, average 309 mm) (Table I). A black crust was described in Polyporus nigro-applanatus van der Byl (1924) but the type of the latter was not available for comparison, and we are not confident of its status. We therefore consider it as synonym of P. vicina, following Reid (1973; 1975) and Ryvarden and Johansen (1980).  Within the known range of occurrence (South and East Africa), P. vicina can be compared to Vanderbylia ungulata Reid (1973), a taxon usually known under Perenniporia mundula (Wakef.) Ryvarden (Ryvarden and Johansen, 1980). V. ungulata is characterized by large, perennial basidiocarp, with stratified pore layers and a thick black crust often becoming rimose with age, smaller basidiospores (5.5-6.8 x 5.2-6.2 µm

Basidiospores thin-to slightly thick-walled, ornamented with verruculae (rounded warts) or short echinulae (sharp spines), or a mixture of both. Distribution basically temperate. OBSERVATIONS: This group of taxa is rather easily separated from section Dendrocladium, but seems to resemble some members of subg. Lentoramaria. In fact, fruitbodies of R. suecica (Fr.) Donk, are easily confused with luxuriant individuals of R. invalii (see above under "Phylogenetic relationships" for more on this). Killermann did not explicitly state the rank of his subsect. terrestres. Likewise, Corner (1970: 239) diagnosed his series Virescentes in terms of series Flaccidae. It seems wise, therefore, to elevate the latter name to oppose Sect. Dendrocladium. The group is difficult to diagnose. In examining hundreds of specimens microscopically, it is easy to be convinced that all spore ornamentation in the group is of spines, for on such has the group been defined (Corner, 1950: Coker, 1923, etc.), and the ornamentation often falls just at the edge of microscopic resolution. When viewed through the scanning electron microscope, however, ornamentation is seen to vary from sharp spines (occasionally volcanic) to rounded warts.The latter come close to the pattern on some spores in subg. Lentoramaria, making written diagnoses more difficult. As with Sect. Dendrocladium, I can offer only the following list of guidelines to circumscribe Sect. Flaccidae: 1. Fruitbodies ocher, tan, honey-color to occasionally greenish ocher, showing no bruising reactions, but sometimes suffusing with green or olive colors after exposure to air. 2. Fruitbodies arising from a more or less extensive tangle of rhizomorphic strands. 3. Spores ornamented with discrete rounded warts of a mixture of warts and short spines. 4. Spores thin-walled, usually less than 8 µm

(basionym: Hyphoderma vulcanense Gilb. & Adask., Mycotaxon 49:376. 1993).  When this taxon was originally described, it was mistakenly thought to be associated with a white rot. Numerous collections made subsequently are associated with a brown rot; therefore, it belongs in the genus Crustoderma. The Michigan and Virginia collections are not conspecific with the type collection. The Virginia collection matches the description published by Burt. It has simpleseptate hyphae and broad vesicles 10-15 µm

basidiospores nor mature basidia were seen. Another collection of this fungus from Maryland is also sterile. The Michigan collection is a third fungus, characterized by thick-walled subicular hyphae 2.03.5 µm

basidiospores 5.7-6.0 mm long in the specimen 1153, which is below the range reported here for the species, and 8.0-9.5 mm for specimen 1154, which fits within our observations. These two STE specimens were not available for comparison and their identity remain uncertain.  P. vicina is characterized by a pileate basidiocarp, a dimitic hyphal system with arboriform skeletal hyphae in the tubes trama, subglobose to obovoid, dextrinoid basidiospores with a small "germ pore" opposite the apiculus and dextrinoid chlamydospores.  The two South African specimens examined are very similar, while the Zimbabwean specimen slightly differs. The latter has a more blackish crust developing from the base, and microscopically, has arboriform skeletal hyphae with a longer stalk (up to 450 mm, average 309 mm) (Table I). A black crust was described in Polyporus nigro-applanatus van der Byl (1924) but the type of the latter was not available for comparison, and we are not confident of its status. We therefore consider it as synonym of P. vicina, following Reid (1973; 1975) and Ryvarden and Johansen (1980).  Within the known range of occurrence (South and East Africa), P. vicina can be compared to Vanderbylia ungulata Reid (1973), a taxon usually known under Perenniporia mundula (Wakef.) Ryvarden (Ryvarden and Johansen, 1980). V. ungulata is characterized by large, perennial basidiocarp, with stratified pore layers and a thick black crust often becoming rimose with age, smaller basidiospores (5.5-6.8 x 5.2-6.2 µm

basidiospores in the lumina. Pores 1-3 mm diam, angular, with edges being entire or lacerate, thin; poroid surface concolorous with that formed by the tubular profiles. Stipe solid or tubular, sometimes branched, giving origin to separate pilei or forming a single pileus on top. Microscopic characteristics. Pilear cover (Fig. 10b) a cortex formed by hyphae slightly inclined to the context hyphae, predominantly composed of skeletal, subhyaline to yellowish, thick-walled, intermingled with generative, clamped, thinwalled, usually collapsed hyphae. Peripherally the hyphae agglutinated by an exudate making them darker, but exudate not oozing onto the surface. Cortex slightly incrusted peripherally in old basidiocarps. Context composed mainly of hyaline, subhyaline to yellowish, hyphae; generative hyphae clamped, hyaline, thin-walled, 2-4(-5) µm

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). Patouillard & Gaillard (1888: 27) reported the species in Venezuela and indicated the basidiospores as hyaline and 6-7 µm

basidiospores and the hyphal system support a place in Perenniporia as usually defined (Decock & Ryvarden 1999, 2000, Gilbertson & Ryvarden 1987, Ryvarden & Gilbertson 1994, Ryvarden & Johansen 1980).  The hyphal system is mainly dimitic with yellowish, variably branched vegetative hyphae. Narrow, binding-1ike hyphae are present in the context, and then especially in its dense, darker thin zones. They are much more scattered in the other parts.  Within the African Perenniporia species, P. mundula (Wakef.) Ryvarden (Ryvarden 1977) and P. tephropora (Mont.) Ryvarden (Ryvarden & Johansen 1980) have a related hyphal system and similar basidiospores morphology. Perenniporia mundula, known only from the type collection originating in Zimbabwe, differs from P. centrali-africana by possessing a light coloured (white to pale creamy) context and tube layer. The former is closely related to P. medulla-panis (Jacq.: Fr.) Donk, type species of Perenniporia. Perenniporia tephropora shares with P. centrali-africana a brown context and tube layer but differs by possessing a primarily resupinate basidiocarp, occasionally developing black pseudopilei at the upper margin of perennial specimens, a greyish to grey pore surface, and smaller basidiospores (Ryvarden & Johansen 1980). Perenniporia inflexibilis (Berk.) Ryvarden is a species that usually develops a completely resupinate basidiocarp. However, occasionally, the species is found in a pileate form, which then could appear, macroscopically, rather similar to P. centrali-africana, with a sulcate, light brown pileus and a greyish brown context and tube layers. Perenniporia inflexibilis differs, however, from the latter by having a greyish to grey pore surface, different vegetative hyphae, and more globose, non-to only faintly dextrinoid basidiospores (Corner 1989, Ryvarden & Johansen 1980).  The paratype specimen of P. centrali-africana (Wat. 22777, Makeke, South West Province) was first reported as Perenniporia contraria (Berk. & Cooke) Ryvarden by Hjortstam et al. (1993). The latter is, however, a different, very distinct taxon, mainly characterised by a pileate, brown basidiocarp, a white to creamy context and tube layer, and microscopically by possessing completely unbranched, hyaline, strongly dextrinoid skeletal hyphae, and small (on average less than 5 µm

basidiospores in the lumina. Pores 1-3 mm diam, angular, with edges being entire or lacerate, thin; poroid surface concolorous with that formed by the tubular profiles. Stipe solid or tubular, sometimes branched, giving origin to separate pilei or forming a single pileus on top. Microscopic characteristics. Pilear cover (Fig. 10b) a cortex formed by hyphae slightly inclined to the context hyphae, predominantly composed of skeletal, subhyaline to yellowish, thick-walled, intermingled with generative, clamped, thinwalled, usually collapsed hyphae. Peripherally the hyphae agglutinated by an exudate making them darker, but exudate not oozing onto the surface. Cortex slightly incrusted peripherally in old basidiocarps. Context composed mainly of hyaline, subhyaline to yellowish, hyphae; generative hyphae clamped, hyaline, thin-walled, 2-4(-5) µm

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). Patouillard & Gaillard (1888: 27) reported the species in Venezuela and indicated the basidiospores as hyaline and 6-7 µm

basidiospores in the lumina. Pores 1-3 mm diam, angular, with edges being entire or lacerate, thin; poroid surface concolorous with that formed by the tubular profiles. Stipe solid or tubular, sometimes branched, giving origin to separate pilei or forming a single pileus on top. Microscopic characteristics. Pilear cover (Fig. 10b) a cortex formed by hyphae slightly inclined to the context hyphae, predominantly composed of skeletal, subhyaline to yellowish, thick-walled, intermingled with generative, clamped, thinwalled, usually collapsed hyphae. Peripherally the hyphae agglutinated by an exudate making them darker, but exudate not oozing onto the surface. Cortex slightly incrusted peripherally in old basidiocarps. NEW ZEALAND. Otago, Ulva, Stewart Island, on bark of Weinmannia racemosa Linn.f., 18 Feb. 1954, J.M. Dingley, PDD 18041 (holotype of Odontia tessellata: PDD). This striking species is immediately identifiable because of the stratified, rimose, dense basidiomes with rounded tubercules, encrusted, thick-walled cystidia, and small, ellipsoid basidiospores. Although the holotype specimen of O. latemarginata lacks basidia, it is otherwise morphologically similar to S. loricata and O. tessellata. The holotype specimen of Odontia tessellata is a particularly fine, extensively rimose, and well-developed specimen with the largest piece measuring 15 x 7 cm. The paratype specimen of S. loricata from Ecuador (on wood, T. Laessoe TL-155, K(M) 55757 (K)) differs from the holotype specimen of S. loricata by its longer (up to 2 mm), brittle, smooth, cylindrical spines, slightly shorter and narrower cystidia (25-50 x 5-6.5 µm),

basidiospores together distinguish Hyphodontia ochroflava from other species of Hyphodontia. An unusual feature of H. ochroflava is the development of lagenocystidia on vegetative hyphae at the base of the spines. These lagenocystidia are produced laterally, at right angles on supporting hyphae and often lack the characteristic flask shape. Another important feature is the somewhat thick-to thick-walled tramal hyphae of the central spine that superficially resemble skeletal hyphae. Hyphodontia ochroflava is closely related to H. arguta (Fr.) John Erikss. that possesses significantly broader basidiospores (4.5-6 x 3.5-4 µm).

Basidiospores (5.5) 6.7-7.6-8.1-8.6 (9.5)-(5.3) 6.4-7.1-7.6-8.1 (8.8) ?m (Q = 1.01-1.06-1.17; n = 100), globose to subglobose; ornamentation amyloid, forming an incomplete to almost complete reticulum with rather wide meshes, composed of firm ridges; ridges often with a slightly split aspect, < 2-2.5 ?m high, mostly with smooth or somewhat irregular edges, sometimes slightly crenulate; minute isolated warts present between the ridges; plage mostly distally amyloid. Basidia 40-70-10-15 ?m, subclavate to clavate, 4-spored, hyaline sometimes with guttate contents; sterigmata 3-6-1-2 ?m. Pleuromacrocystidia abundant to very abundant, 40-80(95)-8-13 ?m, emergent, subcylindrical, subclavate or subfusiform, apex obtuse, acute, capitate or submoniliform, containing needle-1ike crystals, thin-walled. Pleuropseudocystidia abundant to moderately abundant, 2.5-5.5(6) ?m diam., not or slightly emergent, slender, cylindrical, tortuous, thin-walled. Lamellar edge mostly sterile, sometimes basidia present but mainly composed of cheiloleptocystidia and cheilomacrocystidia; cheilomacrocystidia abundant, 40-60-9-11 ?m, subclavate to fusiform, similar to pleuromacrocystidia, contents granular or with needle-1ike crystals, thin-walled; cheiloleptocystidia 10-25-2.5-8 ?m, cylindrical to subfusiform or narrowly clavate, hyaline, thin-walled. Hymenophoral trama predominantly filamentous; lactifers abundant. Pileipellis a palisade, 60-90 ?m thick, hyaline or containing a faint brownish intracellular pigmentation in the upper layers; suprapellis composed of subcylindrical, terminal elements that are 10-50-2-6.5 µm,

Basidiospores are produced on well-developed sterigmata both laterally and apically on the basidia. basidiospores of A. canadensis are ellipsoid and rounded at both ends, whereas spores in A. fennicus are distinctly flattened adaxially and taper toward the apiculus. The macrocystidia of A. fennicus are generally flexuous-cylindric to subclavate, whereas the macrocystidia found in A. canadensis are regularly one to several moniliform toward the apex. Spore dimensions cited for European material of this species are rather small for the North American material (fide Laurila, 10-14 x 7-9 µm).

basidiospores ornamented by isolated groups of narrow cones that adhere together to form secondary spines, and an association with Pinus kesiya. Type: Thailand. Chang Mai, Hot District, Bo Kaew pine plantation, under Pinus kesiya, 11-Aug-2001 (holotype, BBH 28597; GenBank FR748148). Basidiome: 35-55 mm high, pedicellate to broadly clavate, divided into distinct head and cylindrical stipe, snuff-brown to cigar-brown with a black shining surface around the head, surface smooth, not scaly. Peridium: 24-45 mm broad, broadly ellipsoid to subglobose, rough, thin, brittle, snuff-brown, breaking up at the apex to expose powdery contents and join up to stipe. Stipe: 13-24 x 10-15 mm woody, snuff-brown, smooth, cylindrical base of agglutinate mycelium and soil, yellowish rhizomorphs when immature. Gleba: snuffbrown to ferruginous powdery mass formed by the breakdown of peridioles seated in a small black pocket within the peridium. Peridioles: thin-walled, ovoid-ellipsoid, smooth, clay-buff, 2 x 1 mm, at first clay-buff then more snuffbrown or ferruginous as they mature, discrete, but later breaking down into a snuff brown to ferruginous powdery mass, exuding sienna to fulvous fluid when mounted in alkaline solution. Constituent hyphae: intertwined, hyaline to ochraceous, thin-walled, 2.4-4.8 mm broad, septate without encrustation, clamp-connections present. Basidia not seen. Basidiospores: globose, 5.8-9.0-10.7 µm

basidiospores and lack of incrusting pigment in the pileus tramal hyphae. Type: Guyana. Region 8: Potaro-Siparuni. Pakaraima Mountains. Upper Potaro River Basin, ~20 km east of Mt. Ayanganna, Tadang Base Camp 2 km south of Potaro River at 5º16′14.5″N 59º50′39.1″W, elevation 710-750 m; vicinity of base camp, 21 December 2009, Henkel 9116 (BRG, holotype; HSU, isotype). Pileus 6-16.5 mm broad, 3-4.5 mm high, broadly convex to plano-convex to plane, somewhat flattened across apex and subumbilicate, glabrous, translucent striate from disc to margin, overall pale orangish white (4A2-4A3) to greyish orange (4B4-4B5) with age, moist; disc hygrophanous with medium grey cast; margin irregularly crenulate. Lamellae subclose, subthin, adnexed to barely adnate, 3-5 mm long, 0.5-2.0 mm tall, off-white at first (4A1-4A2), developing slight pinkish overtones (~5A3) with age; margins concolorous, nearly smooth under hand lens; lamellulae consistently 3 between lamellae, 0.5-2 mm long, in 2 tiers. Stipe 25-53 x 1-2 mm at apex, 2-4 mm at base, tapering upward, translucent, off-white (4A1-4A2) to pale light yellow (4A4), slightly yellowing (3A3-3A4) where handled, glabrous, hollow. Basal mycelium scant, white, and hispid at extreme base. Odor none; taste not noted. Basidiospores distinctly 5-6(-7)-angled and heterodiametric in profile view, 7.7-10.8 x 5.3-7.8 µm

basidiospores permit a distinction between these two taxa, however. In A. praetervisum they are hyaline to subhyaline, sometimes faintly yellowish, especially when in mass, and have faintly evident endosporic projections. In A. omphalodes the spores have thicker walls, very conspicuous endosporic projections and are distinctly yellowish. When the basidiospores are lighter in A. omphalodes, it usually correlates that the basidiocarp is in the process of development and the context is almost white, which allows a distinction of the species from A. praetervisum. Specimens identified as A. omphalodes have been mentioned by several authors (Patouillard, 1889: 77; Lloyd, 19.12: 113; Bresadola, 1916: 239; Torrend, 1920: 131). basidiospores and narrower contextual hyphae. Type: Australia. Tasmania, Southwest Conservation Area, Warra Long-Term Ecological Research site, ground in mixed forest of Eucalyptus and Nothofagus, 8.VIII.2006 (holotype, TU 103694; isotype, BJFC; European Nucleotide Archive accession number, AM412243 for nLSU). Basidiocarps annual, centrally stipitate, gregarious. Pileus more or less circular, infundibuliform, up to 3 cm in diam., 3 mm thick at centre. Pileal surface cinnamon to greyish brown, concentrically zonate, when dry with radial wrinkled ridges, glabrous; margin thin, acute, curving down when dry. Pore surface reddish brown to greyish brown; pores angular, 3-4 per mm; dissepiments thin, entire. Context dark brown, coriaceous, up to 1 mm thick. Tubes yellowish brown, paler than the context, fragile when dry, up to 2 mm long. Stipe yellowish brown, matted, up to 3 cm long and 2 mm in diam. Hyphal system monomitic; generative hyphae simple septate; tissue becoming reddish brown in KOH but otherwise unchanged. Contextual hyphae pale yellowish to golden brown, thick-walled with a wide lumen, regularly branched and septate, straight, regularly arranged, 3.5-6.5 µm

basidiospores and non-encrusting pigment in pileipellis. Type: China, Yunnan Province, Jingdong County, Ailaoshan National Nature Reserve, 14 July 2008, Yanchun Li 1213 (Holotype, HKAS 56067). Pileus 30-40 mm broad, convex at first, then applanate, tawny gray or grayish brown to brown (6D3, 6D-E5); brown (6E5) overall under lens, tomentose; margin incurved, not striate. Lamellae white but soon pale flesh-pink to pink (7A1-2), decurrent, close to crowded; edges concolorous and even; lamellulae numerous. Stipe paler than pileus to partially concolorous with pileus, orange gray (6B2), brownish orange (6C3) to light brown (6D4), with white (6A1) cottony mycelium at the base, 35-45 mm long, 4-6 mm thick at the apex, 7-12 mm thick at the base, tomentose, inconspicuously striate, central to slightly eccentric, often slightly curved, cylindrical, usually broadening towards base. Context white (6A1), unchanging when bruised or exposed to air. Basidiospores 11-13(-14) x (5-)5.5-6.5(-7) µm,

basidiospores in the genus. Type.-China. Taiwan Prov., Hualian County, Lintianshan Forest Farm, on rotten gymnosperm wood, 22.XI.2009 Dai 11560 (holotype, BJFC). Etymology.-taiwanense (Lat.) refers to the type locality of Taiwan. Fruiting body.-Basidiocarps perennial, resupinate to effused-reflexed, broadly elongated along substrates, coriaceous and tough, without special odor when fresh; resupinate part loosely adnate, up to 10 cm long, 4 cm wide; pilei projecting up to 3 cm and 2.3 cm thick at the base; pileal surface concentrically zonate and sulcate, glabrous, at first ochraceous to brown, becoming grayish brown to black with age; margin sharp; pore surface cinnamon to brown; pores angular to slightly daedaleoid, 1-2 per mm; single pore up to 4 mm long and 1 mm wide when daedaleoid; tubes up to 20 mm long, mostly with white pruinose walls; context brown to dark brown, coriaceous, up to 3 mm thick. Hyphal structure.-Hyphal system dimitic; generative hyphae with distinct clamp connections, hyphae IKI-, CB-; tissue darkening but otherwise unchanged in KOH. Context.-Context dominated by skeletal hyphae; generative hyphae hyaline, thin-to slightly thick-walled, moderately branched, 2-4 µm
Spores.-Basidiospores cylindrical, hyaline, thin-walled, smooth, IKI-, CB-, (5.5-)5.8-7(-7.3) x 2.5-3 µm,

basidiospores on the surface of the agar. After 2 wk on MEA colonies are planar, uniform, pink with diffuse margins; on M40Y colonies are flat, plicate, pink with diffuse margins; on DG18 colonies are flat, pink with diffuse or discrete margins.  Basidium-bearing cells (primary cells) at first are irregularly shaped on terminal and lateral branches of hyphae. Over time they expand and mature into swollen and irregularly shaped primary cells attached to hyphae by a thin connector. Mature primary cells are 14.5-17.0 x 11.0-12.0 µm

basidiospores with larger ornamentations. Type: China. Sichuan Province, from Rangtang County to Seda County, banks of Duke River, 5.VIII.2007, Z.W. Ge1707 (Holotype, HKAS53792, GenBank JX391969) Basidiomata semi-hypogeous to epigeous, russuloid to secotioid, small. Pileus 3.1-4.4 cm in diam., irregularly globose to subglobose when young, hemispheric, barely expanded, sometimes pulvinate when mature, centre slightly depressed with age, whitish, dirty-white to pale-pinkish tinge of Pale Salmon Color (XIV9ʹf) to Pale Flesh Color (XIV7ʹf), rarely with greenish tinge of Dark Olive Buff (XL21ʹʹʹ), intermixed with brown to olivaceous brown tinge of Wood Brown (XL17ʹʹʹ), Brussels Brown (III15m) when dry; margin whitish to cream, White (LIII) to Cream color (XVI19ʹf), often glabrous, dry, slightly viscid when moist, strongly incurved and indented around the stipe, sometimes slightly radially rugose, with slightly pinkish tinge of Pale Flesh Color (XIV7ʹf), not striate. Context ≤3 mm at the disc, whitish, fragile; odor not distinctive; taste mild. Lamellae/Gleba 3-6 mm high, sublamellate to lamellate, composed of sinuate, contorted, very crowded, convoluted lamellae, often exposed near the stipe, cream to yellowish tinge of Pale Orange-Yellow (III15f) when juvenile, with pale orange tinge of Orange Buff (III15d) to Light Orange-Yellow (III17d) when mature. Stipe 4.0-6.0 x 1.0-1.5 cm, subcylindrical, surface dry, rugulose longitudinally, dull, without annulus, slightly attenuate upwards, whitish, ≤3 mm at pileus diameter, stuffed first, becoming hollow when old. Spore print ocher to yellow (Romagnesi IIIc-1Va). Basidiospores [100/3/2] (8.8-)9.4-14.1(-15.5) x (7.6-)7.9-12.8(-13.1) µm,

basidiospores and from A. thibetanus by its wrinkled to shallowly reticulate pileus surface and the absence of appendiculate veil remnants. Type: China, Guangxi Province, Mao’ershan National Nature Reserve, 25º50′N 110º19′E, 1387 m alt., on soil in a broadleaved forest dominated by Fagaceae (Cyclobalanopsis sp.), 16 July 2012, Ming Zhang (Holotype, GDGM 42601, GenBank KF534789). Basidiomes slender. Pileus 20-35 mm broad, hemispherical when young, becoming broadly convex to nearly plane in age, strongly glutinous when fresh, distinctly wrinkled to irregularly and shallowly reticulate, brown to reddishbrown (6D8-8D8, 8E8) at center and gradually paler outwards, deep orange (5A8-6A8), orange (5A7-6A7), orange-yellow (4A8-4A7), light yellow to pale yellow (3A4-4A4) at margin, with a slightly incurved edge when young. Context 3-4 mm thick at the centre of the pileus, thinner at pileus margin, soft, white to yellowish-white (1A1-1A2), more or less brown beneath the pileipellis, slightly changing pinkish-white (7A2-9A2) to pale red (7A3-9A3) when exposed. Tubes slightly depressed around stipe, light yellow to greenishyellow (2A5, 2B5), 8-10 mm deep, unchanging on bruising. Pores 0.8-1 mm in diam., roundish to angular, somewhat compound and relatively larger around the stipe, concolorous with tubes. Stipe 40-70 x 3-7 mm, central, cylindrical, sometimes hollow and usually tapering towards the base, greyishred to brownish-orange (7C4-7D4), smooth, without reticulation, sometimes longitudinally striate, gelatinous or strongly viscid, especially when young and wet, with a white (1A1) basal mycelium. It is phylogenetically and ecologically divergent from Hebeloma youngii.  Pileus 3-32 mm diam, at first broadly conic with the margin slightly inrolled, later expanding and becoming convex, smooth, lacking an umbo; reddish brown to buff (5YR 4/6-7.5YR 8/4) at the pileus center, becoming pale buff to cream (10YR 8/3) toward the margin; a pale whitish veil is present before expansion. Lamellae 0.5-1.5 mm wide (dry material), narrowly attached, close, with even concolorous edge; pallid or pale pinkish brown when young, dull pinkish brown (5YR 7/4) at maturity, lamellulae 1-2 mm long. Stipe 9-39 x 2-7 mm, central, terete, equal or slightly enlarged toward the base, hollow, pliant; surface finely pruinose over the upper third of the stipe, otherwise lightly longitudinally fibrillose with faint annular cortinate remains present, some fibrils and the remains of the cortina become brownish mostly from spore deposits; stipe light buff to cream (10YR 8/3-8/2), the base becoming reddish brown (5YR 4/4) at maturity. Dried spore print on white paper dull reddish brown (5YR 5/3). Odor faintly fungoid to acidulous. Context pallid, no color changes observed.  Basidiospores 9.0(10.6) 11.0 x 5.5 (6.8)7.5 µm,

basidiospores and from L. croceigalus by its very crowded light yellow lamellae that turn light orange to orange when bruised, its unbranched pleuropseudocystidia, and its lack of pileopseudocystidia. Type: India. Sikkim: North District, Bansoi, 27°41′56.2″N 88°34′10.6″E, alt. 2323 m, 31.VII.2013, K. Das, KD-13-84 (Holotype, CAL). Pileus 58-75 mm diam., convex when young, becoming planoconvex to shallowly depressed or slightly infundibuliform, never umbonate; surface rough to subvelutinous, mostly radially wrinkled, dry to moist, never viscid, light brown (6D4) to greyish brown (6D3) or sometimes pale yellow (4A3) to greyish yellow (4B3); margin decurved to incurved, irregularly wavy or interrupted at maturity. Lamellae narrowly adnate to subdecurrent, very crowded (23/cm at pileus-margin), brittle, light yellow (4A4), turning light orange (5A5) to orange (5A7) when bruised; edge smooth but, minutely hairy (under stereo-zoom microscope), concolorous; lamellulae abundant, in 7-8 series. Stipe 55-75 x 8-13 mm, central, more or less cylindrical with tapering base; surface more or less smooth, yellowish white (4A2) at apex, towards base greyish orange (5B3) to brownish orange (5C4) or concolorous to pileus, then paler to pale yellow (4A3) near base and finally white at base, turning light orange (5A5) when bruised. Context white, becoming pale yellow (4A3), light orange (5A4) or darker when exposed, turning pale orange (5A3) with FeSO4, reddish brown (8D7) with guaiacol and yellowish white (1A2) to pale yellow (1A3) with KOH. Latex abundant, white, unchanging when kept isolated, turning yellowish white with KOH but, on contact with the cut lamellae becoming pinkish white (7A2) after 3-4 minutes, then finally (or after drying) reddish orange (7A6). Odor indistinctive. Taste slightly sour initially, then acrid. Spore print light yellow (4A4). Basidiospores 7.0-7.5-8.5 x 6.5-7.1-8.0 µm

basidiospores broadly ellipsoidal to ovoid, thick-walled, yellow but turning chestnut in KOH solution. Producing a white rot in the substrate.  Basidiome annual to reviving, resupinate to effused-reflexed, small or covering up to 30 x 7 cm surface in a continuous body, generally forming reflexed pilei in the upper and lateral margins and, when formed, pilei appearing first as if nodular but developing into broadly attached and semicircular bodies, 2.5-4 cm wide, 1.2-1.8 cm radius and up to 1.5 cm thick at the base, or pilei elongated; the margins blunt and up to 2-3 mm thick. Pilear surface pubescent to strigose at the base, but loosing the hairs with age and then surface indurated, lacking a crust, cracked or not, hairy portions light tobacco, glabrous portions dark brown with black striae. Pores generally roundish to irregular, subgyrose, 3-3.5(-4.5)/mm, light tobacco brown to yellowish brown when newly developed, turning dark chestnut brown upon maturity, with pore mouths ashy gray. Context thin in resupinate portions, but up to 8 mm thick in pileate specimens, without a granular core, milk chocolate brown to dark reddish brown, sometimes developing a black line under the pilear surface restricted to reflexed portions. Tubes up to 12 mm long. Hyphal system monomitic. Generative hyphae simple-septate, 2-3(-4) µm

basidiospores and its stipe covered by heavily fibrillose scales. Type: China, Yunnan Province, Yingjiang County, Tongbiguan National Natural Reserve, 19 July 2013, collected by Qing-Hua Yu ZRL201332 (Holotype HMAS; isotype, SWFC; GenBank, KM889913). Pileus 25-35 mm diam., broadly and obtusely conical when young, then expanding to 45-55 mm in diam., convex and subumbonate; margin recurved, crenate, splitting with age, rarely uplifted; surface dry, covered with dense fibrillose-scales, recurved, reddish-brown against the whitish background. Context 2 mm thick, white. Lamellae free, crowded, with 2-4 series of lamellulae, 2-4 mm broad, at first white, then grayish white, finally dull brown, edges even entire. Stipe 42-126 x 5-8(-10) mm, cylindrical, sometimes with basal rhizomorphs, hollow, surface above annulus glabrous to fibrillose, below annulus floccose, scaly, white. Annulus pendent, single, membranous, superior, edge entire, persistent, white, 4-6 mm broad, upside smooth, lower side heavily fibrillose. Odor of seaweed. Staining bright yellow then reddishbrown when bruised or in exposure. Macrochemical reaction: KOH reaction strongly reddish brown, dark brown in stipe. Basidiospores 4.5-6 x 2.5-3.2 µm

Hyphal system dimitic; generative hyphae with clamp connections; skeletal hyphae dextrinoid, CB-; tissues becoming red brown in KOH. Abundant oily substance present in trama. basidiospores with wider germ-pore, broader heads of cheilocystidia and different ecology (grow in needle litter in coniferous forests). Pileus 20 mm broad, obtusely conical, conical-con¬vex or campanulate with slightly undulating mar¬gin; hygrophanous, translucently striate at margin only; brownish orange (6C4-5) with darker light brown (6D8), terra cotta (7D7) centre; surface hardly pruinose, almost smooth. Lamellae distant, narrowly adnate, hardly ventricose, topaz (5C5) to brownish orange (6C8) or rubiginous, with concolourous edge. Stipe 70 x 2 mm, cylindrical, without basal bulb; brown (7E7), agate (7E8) or reddish brown (8E8); longitudinally striate and strongly pruinose. Smell indistinct. Basidiospores 8.4-10 x 5.5-6.5 µm,

basidiospores with peculiar surface ornamentation discerned only in SEM set it apart from similar taxa in sect. Ochromarasmius. Pileus 5-8 mm, at first hemispherical, then conical-convex or conical-campanulate with slightly undulating and sulcate margin and central broad umbo; hygrophanous, translucently striate to centre when moist; in fresh pale ochre, pale yellow (4A3-4), orange yellow (4A8) or greyish yellow (4B5), with darker brownish orange, topaz (5C5-6, 6C8) or brown (6D8) centre, dry dull coloured-brownish beige or greyish brown (6D3, 6E3); surface smooth. Lamellae moderately crowded, narrowly adnate, hardly ventricose, pale yellow-brown to rusty brown, with concolourous edge. Stipe 30-40 x 1-1.5 mm, cylindrical, without basal bulb; whitish at apex or pale cream-yellowish (4A2-3) in lower part; longitudinally striate and slightly pruinose. basidiospores in the genus. Type.-China. Taiwan Prov., Hualian County, Lintianshan Forest Farm, on rotten gymnosperm wood, 22.XI.2009 Dai 11560 (holotype, BJFC). Etymology.-taiwanense (Lat.) refers to the type locality of Taiwan. Fruiting body.-Basidiocarps perennial, resupinate to effused-reflexed, broadly elongated along substrates, coriaceous and tough, without special odor when fresh; resupinate part loosely adnate, up to 10 cm long, 4 cm wide; pilei projecting up to 3 cm and 2.3 cm thick at the base; pileal surface concentrically zonate and sulcate, glabrous, at first ochraceous to brown, becoming grayish brown to black with age; margin sharp; pore surface cinnamon to brown; pores angular to slightly daedaleoid, 1-2 per mm; single pore up to 4 mm long and 1 mm wide when daedaleoid; tubes up to 20 mm long, mostly with white pruinose walls; context brown to dark brown, coriaceous, up to 3 mm thick. Hyphal structure.-Hyphal system dimitic; generative hyphae with distinct clamp connections, hyphae IKI-, CB-; tissue darkening but otherwise unchanged in KOH. Context.-Context dominated by skeletal hyphae; generative hyphae hyaline, thin-to slightly thick-walled, moderately branched, 2-4 µm
